drug.desc:
Clopidogrel is an antiplatelet drug that inhibits clots in coronary artery disease, peripheral vascular disease and cerebrovascular disease. It is prescribed to patients who have been diagnosed with symptomatic atherosclerosis. It may also be prescribed with aspirin to prevent thrombosis following intracoronary stent surgery. Clopidogrel is a pro-drug in that it needs to be metabolised by the CYP2C19 enzyme before it becomes functional. Approximately 14\% of the population have genetic variations for this enzyme that make it slower for the patient’s body to metabolise clopidogrel. The patients may not respond to treatment and are therefore at increased risk for serious adverse events that include death through heart attack and stroke. 
\begin{itemize}
\item A genetic marker for reduced drug efficacy means that a standard dose of the drug does not have an optimal pharmacological effect. 
\item A genetic marker for increased drug efficacy means that a standard dose of the drug has a greater pharmacological effect. 
\item  The absence of a pharmacogenetic marker means normal efficacy with a standard dose is expected.\end{itemize}

Statins are drugs used to lower blood cholesterol (LDL) levels by inhibiting the liver enzyme HMG-CoA reductase. Statins are routinely prescribed to patients with cardiovascular diseases. They are not usually prescribed to individuals who have increased blood cholesterol but who have not been diagnosed with cardiovascular diseases. There are severe adverse drug reactions associated with statins, including myopathy and increased production of liver enzymes. We have tested for genetic variants that affect your sensitivity to the drug and may be used to personalise your dosage if you need to take the drug. The results of many clinical trials have shown that statin therapy is usually safe and the incidence of adverse drug reactions is low. There are however some differences in the speed and dosage that are optimum for individuals. Your genome has been tested for common variants that correspond to differences in your ability to metabolise the statin drug. 
\begin{itemize}
\item A genetic marker for reduced drug efficacy means that a standard dose of the drug does not have an optimal pharmacological effect. 
\item A genetic marker for increased drug efficacy means that a standard dose of the drug has a greater pharmacological effect. 
\item A genetic marker for myopathy corresponds to a risk for an adverse drug reaction. 
\item The absence of a pharmacogenetic marker means normal efficacy with a standard dose is expected. \end{itemize}

Aspirin (acetyl salicylic acid) is the most commonly used antiplatelet drug, and is prescribed for both primary and secondary care of cardiovascular diseases. When patients at high risk for a cardiovascular disease are treated with aspirin, they have a greatly reduced chance (>30\%) of non-fatal myocardial infarction, experience a 25\% reduction in non-fatal stroke and benefit from a significant decrease in mortality. Aspirin works by binding irreversibly to the COX1 enzyme which is involved in the platelet aggregation process. The effect of the drug is not the same on all patients. Some patients who are prescribed aspirin suffer from specific thromboembolic vascular conditions. These adverse reactions are broadly referred to as 'aspirin resistance'. 
\begin{itemize}
\item A genetic marker for reduced drug in an individual indicates that a standard dose of the drug does not have an optimal pharmacological effect. 
\item A genetic marker for increased drug efficacy in an individual indicates that a standard dose of the drug has a greater pharmacological effect on the individual. 
\item The absence of a genetic marker indicates normal efficacy with a standard dose is expected. 
\end{itemize}
